Examples.
As an example, consider the Nomos specification of Fig. [1(a)]In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") expressing the COMPAS property described earlier.
On line [1]line 1In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we specify that we need an input \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1, i.e., a criminal. Lines [2]line 2In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [4]line 4In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") get the first feature of \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1, which corresponds to the number of felonies, and assign it to variable \\lst@ifdisplaystylev1; in variable \\lst@ifdisplaystylev2, we increase this number, and create a new criminal \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2 that differs from \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1 only with respect to this feature, i.e., \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2 has committed more felonies than \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1. Line [5]line 5In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") specifies a precondition that the new criminalâ€™s felonies should not exceed a sensible limit. Lines [6]line 6In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [7]line 7In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") declare two outputs, \\lst@ifdisplaystyled1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystyled2, that are assigned the modelâ€™s prediction when calling it with criminal \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2, respectively (see block of Python code on lines [8]line 8In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [11]line 11In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")). Finally, on line [13]line 13In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we specify the postcondition that the recidivism risk of criminal \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2 should not be lower than that of \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1.

Fig. [1(b)]In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") shows the MNIST specification. Given an image \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1 (line [1]line 1In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")), image \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2 is its blurred version (line [2]line 2In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")), and variable \\lst@ifdisplaystylev1 contains its correct label (line [3]line 3In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")), e.g., retrieved from the dataset. Note that functions such as \\lst@ifdisplaystyleblur and \\lst@ifdisplaystylelabel extend the core Nomos language and may be easily added by the user.
The postcondition on line [10]line 10In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") says that if the blurred image is correctly classified, then so should the original image. Note that we defined a very similar specification for the SpeechCommand propertyâ€”instead of \\lst@ifdisplaystyleblur, we used function \\lst@ifdisplaystylewNoise adding white noise to audio.

The HotelReview specification is shown in Fig. [1(c)]In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"). Note that a hotel review consists of a positive and a negative section, where a guest describes what they liked and did not like about the hotel, respectively. On lines [1]line 1In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [2]line 2In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we obtain two reviews, \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystylex2, and in variables \\lst@ifdisplaystylev1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystylev2 on lines [3]line 3In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [4]line 4In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we store their negative sections (feature \\lst@ifdisplaystyle1 retrieved with function \\lst@ifdisplaystylegetFeat). We then create a third review, \\lst@ifdisplaystylex3, which is the same as \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1 except that its negative section is the concatenation of \\lst@ifdisplaystylev1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystylev2 (lines [5]line 5In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [6]line 6In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")). The postcondition on line [14]line 14In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") checks that the detected sentiment is not more positive for review \\lst@ifdisplaystylex3 than for \\lst@ifdisplaystylex1.

Finally, consider the LunarLander specification in Fig. [1(d)]In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"). On line [1]line 1In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we obtain an input \\lst@ifdisplaystyles1, which is an initial state of the game. Line [2]line 2In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") "relaxes" this state to obtain a new state \\lst@ifdisplaystyles2, which differs from \\lst@ifdisplaystyles1 only in that the height of the lunar surface is lower.
In the block of Python code that follows (lines [5]line 5In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [11]line 11In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")), we initialize outputs \\lst@ifdisplaystyleo1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystyleo2 to zero and play the game from each initial state, \\lst@ifdisplaystyles1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystyles2, in a loop; \\lst@ifdisplaystyleo1 and \\lst@ifdisplaystyleo2 accumulate the number of wins. We use a loop because the environment is stochasticâ€”firing an engine of the lander follows a probability distribution. Therefore, by changing the environment random seed \\lst@ifdisplaystylers on line [8]line 8In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"), we take stochasticity into account. In each loop iteration however, we ensure that the game starting from \\lst@ifdisplaystyles2 is indeed easier, i.e., that stochasticity cannot make it harder, by using the same seed on lines [9]line 9In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models")â€“ [10]line 10In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models"). Note that function \\lst@ifdisplaystyleplay invokes the policy multiple times (i.e., after every step in the game simulator).
Finally, line [13]line 13In Figure 1 â€£ 2 Nomos Specification Language â€£ Specifying and Testing ğ‘˜-Safety Properties for Machine-Learning Models") ensures that, when playing the easier game (starting with \\lst@ifdisplaystyles2), the number of wins should not decrease. Since this property depends on 20 model invocations, it is a 20-safety property! Conversely, we can also make the game harder by "unrelaxing" the original initial state, i.e., increasing the surface height. In such a case, when playing the harder game, the number of wins should not exceed the original number of wins.

